#(iii) Compute the average Conc for each sample
vector_c<-c()
for (r in 1:nrow(concn_file)) {
  #print(paste0(concn_file[r,1]," = ", sum(concn_file[r,2],concn_file[r,3],concn_file[r,4])/3))
  added=0
  for (c in 2:ncol(concn_file)){
    added=added + concn_file[r,c]
  }
  average_sample_concn=added/3
  print(paste0("Average concentration for ", concn_file[r,1]," is ", average_sample_concn))
  vector_c<-c(vector_c, average_sample_concn)
}

#(vii) Write a function to change treatment levels from 0,1,2,3,4 to ”very-low”, ”low”, ”moderate”, 
#”high”, ”very-high” respectively 

change_value <-function(num){
  if (num==0){
    return ("very-low")
  } else if (num==1) {
    return ("low")
  } else if (num==2) {
    return ("moderate")
  } else if (num==3) {
    return ("high")
  } else {
    return ("very-high")
  }
}

#use this with sapply() or other appropriate function to change treatment variable in combined dataset

new_file <- left_join(meta_file,concn_file, by="samples")
#change_value(3)
#sapply(meta_file$Treatment, change_value)
new_file[["Treatment"]] <- sapply(new_file[["Treatment"]], change_value)
print(new_file)

# Optional function created to change dataframe column at once. Now checking how fast it is
#to compare it to both for loop and sapply()

new_file <- left_join(meta_file,concn_file, by="samples") 
change_column_in_dataframe <- function(dataframe, column_name) {
  if (column_name %in% colnames(dataframe)) {
    col_index <- which(colnames(dataframe) == column_name)
    for (col in 1:ncol(dataframe)){
     if (col == col_index){
       for (row in 1:nrow(dataframe)){
           if (dataframe[[row,col_index]]==0){
           dataframe[[row,col_index]] <- "very-low"
         } else if (dataframe[[row,col_index]]==1) {
           dataframe[[row,col_index]] <-"low"
         } else if (dataframe[[row,col_index]]==2) {
           dataframe[[row,col_index]] <- "moderate"
         } else if (dataframe[[row,col_index]]==3) {
           dataframe[[row,col_index]] <- "high"
         } else {
          dataframe[[row,col_index]] <- "very-high"
          }
        }
      }
    }
    return(dataframe)
  } else {
    print(paste0(column_name, " is not a column in given data frame ", deparse(substitute(dataframe))))
    return(NULL) 
  }
}
#change_column_in_dataframe(new_file, "Treatment")
#change_column_in_dataframe(new_file, "Treat")
new_file <- change_column_in_dataframe(new_file, "Treatment")

new_file <- left_join(meta_file,concn_file, by="samples") 
print("Time taken to change the column by this other customized change_column_in_dataframe function")
## [1] "Time taken to change the column by this other customized change_column_in_dataframe function"
system.time(new_file <- change_column_in_dataframe(new_file, "Treatment"))
##    user  system elapsed 
##   0.003   0.000   0.002
# From this comparison its evident that the for loop is the slow, a customized function changing #the entire dataframe (created optionally) is fast though not as fast as the sapply run using #another customized single number changing function.

SECTION D (statsFile.csv)

library(report)
stats_file <- read.csv("statsFile.csv")
stats_file <- select(stats_file, Participant=X, BMI, BP, Gender, Status, Location)
#stats_file

# (i) How does BMI relate to BP for the all study participants?

#cor(stats_file$BMI,stats_file$BP)
result_cor <- cor.test(stats_file$BMI, stats_file$BP, method = "pearson")
report(result_cor)
## Effect sizes were labelled following Funder's (2019) recommendations.
## 
## The Pearson's product-moment correlation between stats_file$BMI and
## stats_file$BP is positive, statistically significant, and very large (r = 1.00,
## 95% CI [1.00, 1.00], t(318) = 798.75, p < .001)
#comparison of means
result_t <- t.test(stats_file$BMI, stats_file$BP)
report(result_t)
## Effect sizes were labelled following Cohen's (1988) recommendations.
## 
## The Welch Two Sample t-test testing the difference between stats_file$BMI and
## stats_file$BP (mean of x = 3.19, mean of y = 1.81) suggests that the effect is
## positive, statistically significant, and large (difference = 1.37, 95% CI
## [1.35, 1.39], t(369.13) = 121.36, p < .001; Cohen's d = 9.59, 95% CI [8.88,
## 10.30])
#var(stats_file$BMI,stats_file$BP)
var.test(stats_file$BMI,stats_file$BP)
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  stats_file$BMI and stats_file$BP
## F = 12.648, num df = 319, denom df = 319, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  10.15190 15.75872
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##           12.64836
#Above results suggest presence of relationsip between BMI and BP.

#Results show no significance between gender and disease status

# (iii) Construct an appropriate model to show the relationship between BMI and BP

fit.model <- lm (BMI ~ BP, data = stats_file)
report(fit.model)
## We fitted a linear model (estimated using OLS) to predict BMI with BP (formula:
## BMI ~ BP). The model explains a statistically significant and substantial
## proportion of variance (R2 = 1.00, F(1, 318) = 6.38e+05, p < .001, adj. R2 =
## 1.00). The model's intercept, corresponding to BP = 0, is at -3.26 (95% CI
## [-3.28, -3.25], t(318) = -404.03, p < .001). Within this model:
## 
##   - The effect of BP is statistically significant and positive (beta = 3.56, 95%
## CI [3.55, 3.56], t(318) = 798.75, p < .001; Std. beta = 1.00, 95% CI [1.00,
## 1.00])
## 
## Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized
## version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were
## computed using a Wald t-distribution approximation.
plot(stats_file$BMI, stats_file$BP, main="BMI vs BP", xlab="BMI", ylab = "BP")
abline(coef(fit.model), col="purple")

# (iv) How does BMI compare in the different sampling locations?

# Quick view with box plot
boxplot(stats_file$BMI ~ stats_file$Location, xlab = "BMI", ylab = "Location", col="maroon")

#checking if the variable is parametric ie. normal distribution tendency using a histogram plot
hist(stats_file$BMI, main="BMI histogram", xlab="BMI", col=rainbow(14), lty="dotted")

#checking for normal distribution tendency using a Q-Q plot on BMI variable
qqnorm(stats_file$BMI, main='BMI')
qqline(stats_file$BMI, col="green")

#checking for normal distribution tendency using a Shapiro-Wilk Test
#if p-value is greater than 0.05 then variable is assumed to follow a normal distribution
shapiro.test(stats_file$BMI)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  stats_file$BMI
## W = 0.99643, p-value = 0.6951
#checking for normal distribution tendency using a Kolmogorov-smirnov Test
#if p-value is greater than 0.05 then variable is assumed to be normally distributed
ks.test(stats_file$BMI, 'pnorm', mean=mean(stats_file$BMI), sd=sd(stats_file$BMI))
## 
##  Asymptotic one-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  stats_file$BMI
## D = 0.035688, p-value = 0.8097
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided
#Thus checking if calculated BMI means by location are the same
stats_file %>% summarise(mean=mean(BMI), .by = Location)
##   Location     mean
## 1        C 3.168441
## 2        B 3.207686
## 3        A 3.177883
#checking variance
stats_file %>% summarise(variance=var(BMI), .by = Location)
##   Location   variance
## 1        C 0.03671136
## 2        B 0.03954995
## 3        A 0.03685191
stats_file$Location <- factor(stats_file$Location, levels = c("A", "B", "C"))
# Now testing with anova to compare BMI with the different sampling locations
anova_results <- aov(BMI ~ Location, data = stats_file)
report(anova_results)
## The ANOVA (formula: BMI ~ Location) suggests that:
## 
##   - The main effect of Location is statistically not significant and very small
## (F(2, 317) = 1.28, p = 0.280; Eta2 = 8.00e-03, 95% CI [0.00, 1.00])
## 
## Effect sizes were labelled following Field's (2013) recommendations.
#(v) How does disease status depend on both BMI and BP?

binary_logistic_regression <- glm(Status ~ BMI + BP, data = stats_file, family =binomial())
report(binary_logistic_regression)
## We fitted a logistic model (estimated using ML) to predict Status with BMI and
## BP (formula: Status ~ BMI + BP). The model's explanatory power is very weak

## = 0, is at -11.64 (95% CI [-180.52, 155.10], p = 0.890). Within this model:

##   - The effect of BMI is statistically non-significant and negative (beta =
## -4.15, 95% CI [-55.88, 46.86], p = 0.873; Std. beta = -0.81, 95% CI [-10.88,
## 9.12])
##   - The effect of BP is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 13.67,
## 95% CI [-167.77, 197.56], p = 0.882; Std. beta = 0.75, 95% CI [-9.18, 10.81])
## 
## Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized
## version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were
